commentBody:
@Cat Lady Margaret --

Very, very funny and oh-so-true.

And as a bonus:  By means of your lovely satire, you managed to make clear to me the faulty reasoning behind the SUNK COST FALLACY in a way that -- at least for me -- the clue didn't.  Now I actually understand what a SUNK COST FALLACY is.

@v 
great challenge, thanks for the workout, ryan judge.
it’s the months of misty grayness and the absence of sunshine that give seattle that reputation. 
@sam lyons (late note re: yesterday’s posts) his name is spelled seigel 
@deb amlen a gentle reminder to change today’s reference to mr. seigel.



emus see a slew of seattle seagulls … and seahawks

@Striker 
Excellent name for the not long to be wee pup, as Sam said. They're a lot of work, but have fun. Training is a must, of course so that Woods is pleasure rather than a burden.

It hurts my heart that these magnificent animals have such short lifespans. We try to make the most of it.

@Foster 

My favorite song on that subject and perhaps any subject:

“I Want My Dog to Live Longer” (Curtis Salgado and Alan Hager:  <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q7-PfzpQcJs" target="_blank">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q7-PfzpQcJs</a>

@K Boose 

LBG is listing the wrong answers they put in those spots.

I'll concur that the top left seemed like the hardest and vaguest part of the puzzle...

@Mike 
The club owner wasn't able to re-coop his losses either.


He had to sell off some of his emus.

@David Connell 
This sounds like me on the days (like today) when I'm trying to justify why I emigrated to Montreal. 



Might be happier with the emus down under.

@Esmerelda - Hmmm… don’t know your starting point. I like variety in all things, including walking out the door not knowing what I might meet.

My friend invited me to play a recital in San Diego. His reason for living there was precisely why I never could: every day, sunshine and moderate temperatures. But I also had this root-level idea of California: wildfires, mudslides, earthquakes, catastrophic events.

There was a world-class drought for months before my flight, wildfires eating away miles of hillsides, then catastrophic rains, mudslides and floods, and, on the very night when I flew out west, an earthquake that dislodged hundreds of pipes in the organ I was to play. I will never understand why people choose to live there.

@Kate 
I had trouble there as well. Even worse, I had a perfectly good answer once I got the B.

John and Paul were both BEATLEs.

@Jim 

Unfortunately, I got the N right off the bat, being a member of a certain generation plagued by that song.

Admit it, emus, you know you sing along…

@xwordtilly -- I just realized that when I was over on The Other Blog and I rushed back here to offer a Mea Culpa, but I see I'm too late.  That's completely on me -- and is one of the DOOKiest DOOKS I've ever seen in the puzzle.

But I'll trade you one SESAMEST for a DRMARTENS which I forgot to mention, but which was another great big "Huh?" for me.  I should know the color of the stitching on a shoe brand?

Anyway, thanks, @xwordtilly, for the gentle and non-judgmental explanation.

@Kenneth Yup. I lived in both Oregon and Washington and it rained a lot in both places. I also have lived in New England, where I am now, and I often point out that the rainfall totals are similar. 

It just takes about three times as many days for that amount of rain to fall in the PNW. It mostly drizzles and mists. 

This is, of course, not so along the PNW coast, where rainfall totals can be 3-4X that of the more interior places like Seattle and Portland.

@lhwp 
I keep being reminded of yet another roadblock....I never parsed that one (and of course 'puppet'  did not evoke Kermit and Gonzo.)
The more, the merrier!

@JP 

The vertical “streak connector line” is to show you how many Tuesdays (for example) that you solved in a row. 

Congratulations on solving today’s and yesterday’s puzzles! They were each tough ones in their own ways. (Actually, Thursday’s might have been easy if I had been able to see the loop-de-loop circles. It was challenging without them.)

@M. Biggen 

One of my law school professors must have been fond of the SUNK COST FALLACY. 

He constantly told those of us who were second-year students that it wasn’t too late to go to dental school. But the third-year students had too much invested in law school to not finish.

